  "mockAnswer": "During a team software project, we were building a recurring payment reminder app and discovered close to our final demo that edited payment dates were causing reminders to fire at incorrect times. Since reminder accuracy was the core value of the app, I took ownership of debugging and fixing the issue before the deadline. I first reproduced the bug across several scenarios and found that the recurrence logic was too tightly coupled to the API flow, which made it hard to test reliably. I proposed moving the date-calculation and scheduling rules into a separate service, then wrote targeted tests for monthly reminders, edited due dates, and custom intervals. After updating the workflow, I worked with a teammate to validate the fix across more than 10 user scenarios. As a result, all planned test cases passed before the demo, reminder timing matched expected dates, and we delivered a stable product presentation. This experience taught me how important modular design and edge-case testing are when building reliable software.",
