{
  "intake": {
    "jobType": "internship",
    "lastName": "Dhillon",
    "position": "Backend Engineering Intern",
    "firstName": "Aman",
    "companyName": "Google",
    "jobDescription": "Backend internship focused on APIs, debugging, distributed systems fundamentals, clean code, and collaboration. Strong candidates communicate clearly, reason through problems, and show ownership in technical projects."
  },
  "transcript": [
    {
      "role": "interviewer",
      "content": "Tell me about a time you faced a backend issue that affected reliability."
    },
    {
      "role": "candidate",
      "content": "During a team project, we built a reminder platform that sent scheduled payment alerts to users. A few days before our final demo, we noticed that some reminder jobs were duplicated, which meant users could receive multiple texts for the same payment. Since reliability was critical to the product, I took ownership of finding the root cause and fixing it before the demo. I traced the issue through our scheduling flow and found that retries from the worker could create duplicate jobs because the job creation logic was not idempotent. I proposed adding a unique job key based on user ID and due date, then updated the backend flow to check for existing pending jobs before inserting a new one. I also added logging around retry behavior and tested the fix across 12 scenarios, including edited dates and repeated submissions. After the fix, duplicate reminders stopped appearing in our test runs, all 12 scenarios passed, and we were able to demo a stable system. It taught me the importance of designing backend flows for idempotency and validating failure cases early."
    }
  ]}

