  "mockAnswer": "In a team backend project, we built a reminder platform that sent scheduled payment alerts to users. A few days before our final demo, we discovered that some jobs were being duplicated, which could cause users to receive multiple reminders for the same payment. Since reliability was central to the product, I took ownership of debugging and fixing the issue before the deadline. I traced the scheduling flow and found that worker retries could recreate jobs because our insertion logic was not idempotent. I proposed adding a unique job key using the user ID and due date, then updated the backend to check for existing pending jobs before creating new ones. I also added logs around retry behavior and validated the fix across 12 scenarios, including edited dates and repeated submissions. As a result, duplicate reminders stopped appearing in our tests, all 12 scenarios passed, and we successfully demoed a stable system. This experience taught me how important idempotency and failure-case testing are in backend development.",
